{"questionId":"33291584","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The next day, Anvi, Vanya and Parita are joined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> additional people in the same restaurant, and they sit in the same row of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math> available seats. Anvi, Vanya and Parita now decide to sit next to each other as a group of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the number of possible ways that these <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> people can be seated.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to multiply ways of seating AVP by ways of sitting additional people<em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>AVP can sit in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> ways (may be seen in part (a))</p>\n<p>other <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> then have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>P</mi><mn>3</mn><mprescripts></mprescripts><mrow></mrow><mn>9</mn></mmultiscripts></mrow></mfenced></math> ways to sit<em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>total ways <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>30240</mn></math><em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: Award <em><strong>(M1)(A0)A0</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>×</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>C</mi><mn>3</mn><mprescripts></mprescripts><mrow></mrow><mn>9</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mn>5040</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to consider ‘AVP’ as one item, so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> ‘items’ in total<em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>C</mi><mn>4</mn><mprescripts></mprescripts><mrow></mrow><mn>10</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>P</mi><mn>4</mn><mprescripts></mprescripts><mrow></mrow><mn>10</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>!</mo><mo>)</mo></math><em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>30240</mn></math><em><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33291584","referenceCode":"24N.2.AHL.TZ0.7b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the number of possible ways that these 6 people can be seated.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.10—Perms and combs, binomial with negative and fractional indices"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}